Edmonds Karp algorithm is traditionally with only one source and one sink. What do you do if you have multiple sources and sinks? This algorithm is a generalized algorithm that regardless of however many sinks and sources you have, will allow you to use this algorithm. It does this by using the traditional algorithm but adding an artificial source and sink that allows with "infinite" weight.

Full Domain Hash Algorithm.
The function with prototype fdh(string,n) generates a hash digest of bitsize = n bits.

This PR adds a suggestion to use gitpod.io for contributing and generally playing around with the algorithms.
We've developed Gitpod to lower friction for collaboration on GitHub and other code hosting platforms by skipping the local setup, maintenance of such and automating workflows. It's free for open-source.
We could configure Gitpod with a Dockerfile so it preinstalls certain tools or python packages, but it looked like most algorithms worked out of the box so I skipped additional configuration.

The class should mimic how page replacement works under LRU caching scheme.

 When a new key is referenced, we add/update it in the cache store.
 If the store runs out of memory and we have to add a new element, the key which was used the least recently should be removed.
 If the user specifies he does not want any memory limit with a None object we should set it as so.
 If specified by a positive integer the store should respect the memory limit.

explored set should not append the root/start outside of the while loop because the root/start is already in explored set and stack would be empty after the first pop. The old version of Fisher-Yates shuffle is wrong.
def FYshuffle(LIST):
    for i in range(len(LIST)):
        a = random.randint(0, len(LIST)-1)
        b = random.randint(0, len(LIST)-1)
        LIST[a], LIST[b] = LIST[b], LIST[a]
    return LIST

If the probability that the second element goes to second last position is 1/n, it's the ideal case.
However, it's not 1/n in this case.
The probability is P(choose the second element) * P(choose the second last element)
= 1/n * 1/n * Sigma(others)
But Sigma(others) < n in this case.

Correct me if I am wrong.
